Over his 20-year career as a designer of visual puzzles, Scott Kim has created hundreds of puzzles for magazines, and thousands for computer games. His puzzles have appeared inside video games such as Obsidian, in browser games like Bejeweled, and in his regular monthly column, The Boggler, in Discover Magazine.

Kim's interest in puzzles sprang from an early interest in mathematics, education and art. He specializes in ambigrams, or inversions: for example, a word that reads more than one way. His first puzzles appeared in Scientific American in Martin Gardner's Mathematical Games column, and are now included in many different books, toys and games. His games can also be played on his website or found on greeting cards. Kim's 1981 book, Inversions, features a collection of "inversions" -- a word or name written so it reads in more than one way. His second book contains a collection of his puzzles originally submitted to magazines and is entitled The New Media Puzzle Workout.

author: Scott_Kim;
title: The art of puzzles

aws-transcripts.transcript: last 20 years, I've been designing puzzles and ah, I'm here today to ah give you a little tour. Starting from the very first puzzle I designed through what I'm doing now. Design puzzles for books, Printed things. I'm the puzzle columnist for Discover magazine. Been doing that for about 10 years. I have a monthly puzzle calendar. I do toys. Bulk of my work is in computer games. I did the puzzles for bejeweled. I didn't invent Bijou old. I can't take credit for that. But so very first puzzle. Sixth grade, my teacher said. Oh, let's see that guy. He likes to make stuff. I'll have him cut out letters out of construction paper for the for the board. I thought this was a great assignment. And so here's what I came up with. I started fiddling with it. It came up this letter. This is a letter of the alphabet that's been folded just once. The question is, which letter is it? If I unfolded and at one hint it's not l. It could be all, of course. So what else could it be? Yeah, a lot of you Got it. Oh, yeah. So clever thing. Now That was my first puzzle. I got hooked. I mean, I created something new at this. I could. I was very excited because, you know, I I had made crossword puzzles, but that's sort of like filling in somebody else's matrix. This was something really original. I got hooked. I read Martin Gardner's columns in Scientific American, went on and eventually decided to devote myself full time to that. Now should pause and say, What do I mean by puzzle? Puzzle is a problem that is fun to solve and has a right answer, fun to solve, as opposed to everyday problems, which, frankly, are not very well designed puzzles, You know that might have a solution might take you a long time. Nobody's wrote down the rules. Clearly, Who designed this? It's like, you know, life is not a very well written story, so we have to hire writers to make movies. Well, I take everyday problems. I make puzzles out of them and right answer. Of course, there might be more than one right answer. Many puzzles have more than but as opposed to a couple other forms of play, toys and games. By toy, I mean something you play with that doesn't have a particular goal. You can create one out of Legos, but you know, you could do anything you want or competitive games like chess, where well, you're not trying to solve. You can make a chest puzzle, but the goal, it really is to eat another player. I consider that puzzles aren't art form. They're very ancient. It goes back as long as there's written history. It's a very small form, like a joke, a poem of a magic trick or a song, very compact form. At worst. You know, they're throwaways there for amusement. But at best they can reach for something Maur and create a memorable impression. The progression of my career that you'll see, is looking for creating puzzles that have a memorable impact. So one thing I found early on why start doing computer games is that I could create puzzles that will alter your perception. I'll show you how here's a famous one.
